---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="Reflection" sideBarActiveItemID="reflection">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto py-12">

    <div class="mb-8">
      <div class="text-3xl w-full font-bold mb-2">Capstone Reflection</div>
      <p class="text-lg text-gray-600">ENGR 499 · Engineering Capstone Design Project</p>
    </div>

    <div class="space-y-4 text-base leading-relaxed">

      <p>
        This course taught me that the design process rarely goes as planned. Midway through our capstone, our team had to scrap
        our existing solution and pivot to an entirely new approach based on a change in client needs. It was difficult in the
        moment, but it reinforced a critical lesson: requirements change, and adaptability is not optional. A cruicial part of engineering
        is adaptability to unforeseen circumstances.
      </p>

      <p>
        In my view, the most important attributes of an engineer are technical competence and collaborative skills.
        Technical ability ensures sound, data-driven decisions. Collaboration is what makes that work effective in a team setting.
        Beyond these, passion for the work matters significantly. A motivated team who believe in the product elevates the whole team. For our product, since it was directly
        related to enhance human healthcare, it was easy to stay motivated and passionate about the work we were doing.
      </p>

      <p>
        This project deepened my understanding of what it means to be a professional engineer in society. Engineers are
        accountable to their clients, teammates, and the people their work ultimately affects. In our case, that was patients
        depending on reliable isotope production, a responsibility that shaped how I approached every design decision.
      </p>

      <p>
        As for my strengths, I bring hands-on capability in firmware development and hardware bring-up, and a willingness to
        take full ownership of my work. I am proud that the Sensor PCB was my very first PCB design, taking it from schematic
        to a working, validated board. The area I need to grow most is documentation. I tend to move
        fast and build (implementer), but thorough documentation is what makes engineering work transferable and professional. Going forward,
        I will treat it as part of the design process, not an afterthought.
      </p>

    </div>

  </div>
</BaseLayout>